This PR provides the necessary API to prove that a condensed set `X` is discrete if and only if
for every profinite set `S = lim·µ¢S·µ¢`, `X(S) ‚âÖ colim·µ¢X(S·µ¢)`, and the analogous result for light
condensed sets.

<!-- By Dependent Issues (Action) - DO NOT REMOVE -->
I have a followup PR #17155 which removes the simp lemma `toProfinite_obj`

```suggestion
colimit, is isomorphic to the presheaf `LocallyConstant _ F(*)`.
```
Or did you mean something else?
The `-` was intended as a "blank". So changed to `LocallyConstant ¬∑ F(*)`.

Most of the `def`s in this PR do not come with `@[simps]` or other forms of equation lemmas/API.

Do you think `@[simps]` just doesn't work well enough? I'm a bit worried that these defn's will be be hard to work with if there are no supporting lemmas at all.

My idea was that one shouldn't interact that much with the `def`s in this file, but rather use the `Condensed.IsDiscrete`¬†typeclass introduced in #14027 and access the equivalent characterizations via the `tfae`¬†statements introduced in that same PR.

But I'll go through this and see if there are some useful simp lemmas to be extracted.
Should this be accompanied by simp lemmas?

I think we rarely have simp lemmas accompanying `def`s of the type `IsColimit`, because it makes you lose access to the nice general `IsColimit` API. In this case it would have the form `(isColimitLocallyConstantPresheaf c X hc).desc s x = s.Œπ.app ‚ãØ.choose ‚ãØ.choose`, which isn't very helpful
I've added lemmas below that are less general than the ones generated by `simps`, but which might be useful to have.

pullRequest.title: feat(Condensed): colimit characterization of discrete condensed sets
